data.content:
Your code **does not use `Thread.Abort`**, `Thread.ResetAbort`, or catch `ThreadAbortException`. The APIs it does use — `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep` — work identically in .NET 8.

No Thread.Abort migration is needed here.

**However**, for a .NET 8 migration, I'd recommend modernizing from raw `Thread` to `Task.Run` + `Parallel.ForEachAsync` or similar, which gives you cleaner cancellation via `CancellationToken`:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items,
        CancellationToken ct = default)
    {
        await Parallel.ForEachAsync(items, ct, async (item, token) =>
        {
            token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
            await Task.Run(() => Process(item), token);
        });
    }

    private void Process(WorkItem item)
    {
        Thread.Sleep(100);
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    }
}
```

This gives you cooperative cancellation — the modern replacement for `Thread.Abort` — if you ever need it in the future.
